# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger] The UNESCO ***Atlas of the World's Languages in Danger*** was an online publication containing a comprehensive list of the world's endangered languages.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger] It originally replaced the ***Red Book of Endangered Languages*** as a title in print after a brief period of overlap before being transferred to an online-only publication.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger] In 1992, the International Congress of Linguists (CIPL) meeting in Canada discussed the topic of endangered languages, as a result of which it formed the Endangered Languages Committee.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger] It held an international meeting also in 1992 in Paris to place the topic before the world and initiate action.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger] The meeting was considered important enough to come under the authority of UNESCO.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger] Shigeru Tsuchida was to start the research center.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger] It began in 1994 at the University of Tokyo with Tasaku Tsunoda as its director.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger] Meanwhile, the initial reports on endangered languages had already been collected and submitted to UNESCO by regional experts in 1993.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger] These have since been turned over to ICHEL, which created a website to enable regular updates to be made available promptly.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger] In February 2009, UNESCO launched an online edition of the *Atlas of Endangered Languages* which covers the whole world, contains much more information than previous printed editions and offers the possibility to users to provide online feedback, in view of its constant updating.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger] Building on this foundation, in 2019 UNESCO launched a new project, the Online World Atlas of Languages (WAL), which will expand the scope beyond endangered languages to document all languages around the world, including sign languages.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger] As of June 2026, the WAL is a work-in-progress and offline until further notice, while the global data set is completed, updates are carried out to improve the platform and enhance its features.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger] Once completed, the WAL will provide a comprehensive, up-to-date resource for researchers, policymakers, and the general public, reflecting the diversity of the world's linguistic heritage and supporting efforts in language preservation and revitalization.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger] As of November 2025, these categories are being reviewed by UNESCO to ensure they reflect the most up-to-date information on language vitality worldwide.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger] Updates aim to provide an accurate and reliable representation of the current status of languages, supporting efforts in documentation, preservation, and revitalization.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Indigenous peoples have continuously inhabited what is now Canada for thousands of years.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Beginning in the 16th century, British and French expeditions explored and later settled along the Atlantic coast.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] As a consequence of various armed conflicts, France ceded nearly all of its colonies in North America in 1763.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In 1867, with the union of three British North American colonies through Confederation, Canada was formed as a federal dominion of four provinces.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] This began an accretion of provinces and territories resulting in the displacement of Indigenous populations, and a process of increasing autonomy from the United Kingdom.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] This increased sovereignty was highlighted by the *Statute of Westminster, 1931*, and culminated in the *Canada Act 1982*, which severed the vestiges of legal dependence on the Parliament of the United Kingdom.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada is a parliamentary democracy and a constitutional monarchy in the Westminster tradition.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The country's head of government is the prime minister, who holds office by virtue of their ability to command the confidence of the elected House of Commons and is appointed by the governor general, representing the monarch of Canada, the ceremonial head of state.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The country is a Commonwealth realm and is officially bilingual (English and French) in the federal jurisdiction.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] It is very highly ranked in international measurements of government transparency, quality of life, economic competitiveness, innovation, education and human rights.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] It is one of the world's most ethnically diverse and multicultural nations, the product of large-scale immigration.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada's long and complex relationship with the United States has had a significant impact on its history, economy, and culture.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] A developed country, Canada has a high nominal per capita income globally and its advanced economy ranks among the largest in the world by nominal GDP, relying chiefly upon its abundant natural resources and well-developed international trade networks.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada is recognized as a middle power; its support for multilateralism and internationalism has been closely related to its foreign policies of peacekeeping and aid for developing countries.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada promotes its domestically shared values through participation in multiple international organizations and forums.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] While a variety of theories have been postulated for the etymological origins of *Canada*, the name is now accepted as coming from the St.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Lawrence Iroquoian word *kanata*, meaning 'village' or 'settlement'.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In 1535, Indigenous inhabitants of the present-day Quebec City region used the word to direct French explorer Jacques Cartier to the village of Stadacona.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Cartier later used the word *Canada* to refer not only to that particular village but to the entire area subject to Donnacona (the chief at Stadacona); by 1545, European books and maps had begun referring to this small region along the Saint Lawrence River as *Canada*.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] From the 16th to the early 18th century, *Canada* referred to the part of New France that lay along the Saint Lawrence River.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Following the British conquest of New France, this area was known as the British Province of Quebec from 1763 to 1791.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In 1791, the area became two British colonies called Upper Canada and Lower Canada.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] These two colonies were collectively referred to as the Canadas until their union as the Province of Canada in 1841.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Upon Confederation in 1867, *Canada* was adopted as the legal name for the new country at the London Conference and the word *dominion* was conferred as the country's title, reflecting its status as a self-governing nation within the British Empire.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Following the London Declaration of 1949, where it was agreed that India could be a full member of the Commonwealth as a republic, not a dominion, the leaders of the Commonwealth countries agreed that the other members of the Commonwealth should not continue to be referred to as *dominions*.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Laurent announced in the Canadian House of Commons that in light of the *Statute of Westminster, 1931*, and the changes to the Commonwealth, *dominion* was no longer an accurate term to use to refer to Canada and would no longer be used by the federal government.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Similarly, the United Kingdom no longer used the term *dominions* to refer to Canada or other members of the Commonwealth, instead beginning to use the term a *realm of the Commonwealth*.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The *Canada Act 1982*, which brought the Constitution of Canada fully under Canadian control, referred only to *Canada*.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Later that year, the name of the national holiday was changed from Dominion Day to Canada Day.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The first inhabitants of North America are generally hypothesized to have migrated from Siberia by way of the Bering land bridge and arrived at least 14,000 years ago.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Paleo-Indian archeological sites at Old Crow Flats and Bluefish Caves are two of the oldest sites of human habitation in Canada.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The characteristics of Indigenous societies included permanent settlements, agriculture, complex societal hierarchies, and trading networks.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Some of these cultures had collapsed by the time European explorers arrived in the late 15th and early 16th centuries and have only been discovered through archeological investigations.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Indigenous peoples in present-day Canada include the First Nations, Inuit, and Métis, the last being of mixed descent who originated in the mid-17th century when First Nations people married European settlers and their offspring subsequently developed their own identity.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Indigenous population at the time of the first European settlements is estimated to have been between 200,000 and two million, with a figure of 500,000 accepted by Canada's Royal Commission on Aboriginal Peoples.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] As a consequence of European colonization, the Indigenous population declined by forty to eighty percent.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Although not without conflict, European Canadians' early interactions with First Nations and Inuit populations were relatively peaceful.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] First Nations and Métis peoples played a critical part in the development of European colonies in Canada, particularly for their role in assisting European coureurs des bois and voyageurs in their explorations of the continent during the North American fur trade.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] These early European interactions with First Nations would change from friendship and peace treaties to the dispossession of Indigenous lands through treaties.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] From the late 18th century, European Canadians forced Indigenous peoples to assimilate into a western Canadian society.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Settler colonialism reached a climax in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] A period of redress began with the formation of a reconciliation commission by the Government of Canada in 2008.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] This included acknowledgment of cultural genocide, settlement agreements, and betterment of racial discrimination issues, such as addressing the plight of missing and murdered Indigenous women.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] It is believed that the first documented European to explore the east coast of Canada was Norse explorer Leif Erikson.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In approximately 1000 AD, the Norse built a small short-lived encampment that was occupied sporadically for perhaps 20 years at L'Anse aux Meadows on the northern tip of Newfoundland.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] No further European exploration occurred until 1497, when seafarer John Cabot explored and claimed Canada's Atlantic coast in the name of Henry VII of England.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In 1534, French explorer Jacques Cartier explored the Gulf of Saint Lawrence where, on July 24, he planted a 10-metre (33 ft) cross bearing the words, "long live the King of France", and took possession of the territory New France in the name of King Francis I.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The early 16th century saw European mariners with navigational techniques pioneered by the Basque and Portuguese establish seasonal whaling and fishing outposts along the Atlantic coast.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In general, early settlements during the Age of Discovery appear to have been short-lived due to a combination of the harsh climate, problems with navigating trade routes and competing outputs in Scandinavia.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In 1583, Sir Humphrey Gilbert, by the royal prerogative of Queen Elizabeth I, founded St John's, Newfoundland, as the first North American English seasonal camp.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In 1600, the French established their first seasonal trading post at Tadoussac along the Saint Lawrence.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] French explorer Samuel de Champlain arrived in 1603 and established the first permanent year-round European settlements at Port Royal (in 1605) and Quebec City (in 1608).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Among the colonists of New France, *Canadiens* extensively settled the Saint Lawrence River valley and Acadians settled the present-day Maritimes, while fur traders and Catholic missionaries explored the Great Lakes, Hudson Bay, and the Mississippi watershed to Louisiana.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Beaver Wars broke out in the mid-17th century over control of the North American fur trade.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The English established additional settlements in Newfoundland in 1610 along with settlements in the Thirteen Colonies to the south.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] A series of four wars erupted in colonial North America between 1689 and 1763; the later wars of the period constituted the North American theatre of the Seven Years' War.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Mainland Nova Scotia came under British rule with the 1713 Treaty of Utrecht and Canada and most of New France came under British rule in 1763 after the Seven Years' War.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Royal Proclamation of 1763 established First Nation treaty rights, created the Province of Quebec out of New France, and annexed Cape Breton Island to Nova Scotia.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] St John's Island (now Prince Edward Island) became a separate colony in 1769.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] To avert conflict in Quebec, the British Parliament passed the Quebec Act 1774, expanding Quebec's territory to the Great Lakes and Ohio Valley.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] More importantly, the Quebec Act afforded Quebec special autonomy and rights of self-administration at a time when the Thirteen Colonies were increasingly agitating against British rule.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] It re-established the French language, Catholic faith, and French civil law there, staving off the growth of an independence movement in contrast to the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Proclamation and the Quebec Act in turn angered many residents of the Thirteen Colonies, further fuelling anti-British sentiment in the years prior to the American Revolution.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] After the American War of Independence, the 1783 Treaty of Paris recognized the independence of the United States and set the terms of peace, ceding British North American territories south of the Great Lakes and east of the Mississippi River to the new country.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The American war of independence also caused a large out-migration of Loyalists, the settlers who had fought against American independence.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Many moved to Canada, particularly Atlantic Canada, where their arrival changed the demographic distribution of the existing territories.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] New Brunswick was in turn split from Nova Scotia as part of a reorganization of Loyalist settlements in the Maritimes, which led to the incorporation of Saint John, New Brunswick, as Canada's first city.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] To accommodate the influx of English-speaking Loyalists in Central Canada, the Constitutional Act of 1791 divided the province of Canada into French-speaking Lower Canada (later Quebec) and English-speaking Upper Canada (later Ontario), granting each its own elected legislative assembly.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Canadas were the main front in the War of 1812 between the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Peace came in 1815; no boundaries were changed.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Immigration resumed at a higher level, with over 960,000 arrivals from Britain between 1815 and 1850.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] New arrivals included refugees escaping the Great Irish Famine as well as Gaelic-speaking Scots displaced by the Highland Clearances.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Infectious diseases killed between 25 and 33 percent of Europeans who immigrated to Canada before 1891.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The desire for responsible government resulted in the abortive Rebellions of 1837.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Durham Report subsequently recommended responsible government and the assimilation of French Canadians into English culture.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Act of Union 1840 merged the Canadas into a united Province of Canada and responsible government was established for all provinces of British North America east of Lake Superior by 1855.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The signing of the Oregon Treaty by Britain and the United States in 1846 ended the Oregon boundary dispute, extending the border westward along the 49th parallel.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] This paved the way for British colonies on Vancouver Island (1849) and in British Columbia (1858).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Anglo-Russian Treaty of Saint Petersburg (1825) established the border along the Pacific coast, but, even after the US Alaska Purchase of 1867, disputes continued about the exact demarcation of the Alaska–Yukon and Alaska–British Columbia border.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Following three constitutional conferences, the *British North America Act, 1867* officially proclaimed Canadian Confederation on July 1, 1867, initially with four provinces: Ontario, Quebec, Nova Scotia, and New Brunswick.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada assumed control of Rupert's Land and the North-Western Territory to form the Northwest Territories, where the Métis' grievances ignited the Red River Rebellion and the creation of the province of Manitoba in July 1870.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] British Columbia and Vancouver Island (which had been united in 1866) joined the confederation in 1871 on the promise of a transcontinental railway extending to Victoria in the province within 10 years, while Prince Edward Island joined in 1873.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In 1898, during the Klondike Gold Rush in the Northwest Territories, Parliament created the Yukon Territory.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Alberta and Saskatchewan became provinces in 1905.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Between 1871 and 1896, almost one quarter of the Canadian population emigrated south to the US.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] To settle the West and attract European immigrants, Canada sponsored the construction of three transcontinental railways, enacted the *Dominion Lands Act* and founded the North-West Mounted Police to maintain regional authority.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] This period of westward expansion and nation building resulted in the displacement of many Indigenous peoples of the Canadian Prairies to "Indian reserves", clearing the way for ethnic European block settlements.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] This caused the collapse of the Plains Bison in western Canada and the introduction of European cattle farms and wheat fields dominating the land.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Indigenous peoples saw widespread famine and disease due to the loss of the bison and their traditional hunting lands.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The federal government did provide emergency relief, on condition of the Indigenous peoples moving to the reserves.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] During this time, Canada introduced the *Indian Act* extending its control over the First Nations to education, government and legal rights.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Because Britain still maintained control of Canada's foreign affairs under the British North America Act, 1867, its declaration of war in 1914 automatically brought Canada into the First World War.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Volunteers sent to the Western Front later became part of the Canadian Corps, which played a substantial role in the Battle of Vimy Ridge and other major engagements of the war.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Conscription Crisis of 1917 erupted when the Unionist Cabinet's proposal to augment the military's dwindling number of active members with conscription was met with vehement objections from French-speaking Quebecers.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In 1919, Canada joined the League of Nations independently of Britain.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Great Depression in Canada during the early 1930s saw an economic downturn, leading to hardship across the country.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In response to the downturn, the Co-operative Commonwealth Federation (CCF) in Saskatchewan introduced many elements of a welfare state (as pioneered by Tommy Douglas) in the 1940s and 1950s.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] On the advice of Prime Minister William Lyon Mackenzie King, war with Germany was declared effective September 10, 1939, by King George VI, seven days after the United Kingdom.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The delay underscored Canada's independence.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The first Canadian Army units arrived in Britain in December 1939.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In all, over a million Canadians served in the armed forces during the Second World War.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canadian troops played important roles in many key battles of the war, including the failed 1942 Dieppe Raid, the Allied invasion of Italy, the Normandy landings, the Battle of Normandy, and the Battle of the Scheldt in 1944.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada provided asylum for the Dutch monarchy while that country was occupied and is credited by the Netherlands for major contributions to its liberation from Nazi Germany.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Despite another conscription crisis in Quebec in 1944, Canada finished the war with a large army and strong economy.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The financial crisis of the Great Depression led the Dominion of Newfoundland to relinquish responsible government in 1934 and become a Crown colony ruled by a British governor.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] After two referendums, Newfoundlanders voted to join Canada in 1949 as a province.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Socially democratic programs were also instituted, such as Medicare, the Canada Pension Plan, and Canada Student Loans; though, provincial governments, particularly Quebec and Alberta, opposed many of these as incursions into their jurisdictions.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Finally, another series of constitutional conferences resulted in the *Canada Act 1982*, the patriation of Canada's constitution from the United Kingdom, concurrent with the creation of the *Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms*.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada had established complete sovereignty as an independent country under its own monarchy.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In 1999, Nunavut became Canada's third territory after a series of negotiations with the federal government.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] At the same time, Quebec underwent profound social and economic changes through the Quiet Revolution of the 1960s, giving birth to a secular nationalist movement.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The radical Front de libération du Québec (FLQ) ignited the October Crisis with a series of bombings and kidnappings in 1970, and the sovereigntist Parti Québécois was elected in 1976, organizing an unsuccessful referendum on sovereignty-association in 1980.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Attempts to accommodate Quebec nationalism constitutionally through the Meech Lake Accord failed in 1990.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] This led to the formation of the Bloc Québécois in Quebec and the invigoration of the Reform Party of Canada in the West.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] A second referendum followed in 1995, in which sovereignty was rejected by a slimmer margin of 50.6 to 49.4 percent.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In 1997, the Supreme Court ruled unilateral secession by a province would be unconstitutional, and the Clarity Act was passed by Parliament, outlining the terms of a negotiated departure from Confederation.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In addition to the issues of Quebec sovereignty, a number of crises shook Canadian society in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada joined the Gulf War in 1990 and was active in several peacekeeping missions in the 1990s, including operations in the Balkans during and after the Yugoslav Wars, and in Somalia, resulting in an incident that has been described as "the darkest era in the history of the Canadian military".
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] After the September 11 attacks in the United States, Canada sent troops to Afghanistan in 2001, resulting in the largest amount of Canadian deaths for any single military mission since the Korean War in the early 1950s.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In 2011, Canadian forces participated in the NATO-led intervention into the Libyan Civil War and also became involved in battling the Islamic State insurgency in Iraq in the mid-2010s.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The COVID-19 pandemic in Canada began on January 27, 2020, causing widespread social and economic disruption.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In 2021, possible gravesites of Indigenous children were found near former Canadian residential schools, highlighting the cultural genocide against Indigenous peoples.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] A trade war involving the United States began on February 1, 2025, when U.S. president Donald Trump signed orders imposing tariffs on goods entering the United States, alongside rhetoric suggesting the annexation of Canada.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] By total area (including its waters), Canada is the second-largest country.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] By land area alone, Canada ranks fourth, due to having the world's largest area of fresh water lakes.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Stretching from the Atlantic Ocean in the east, along the Arctic Ocean to the north, and to the Pacific Ocean in the west, the country encompasses 9,984,670 square kilometres (3,855,100 sq mi) of territory.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada is also home to the world's northernmost settlement, Canadian Forces Station Alert, on the northern tip of Ellesmere Island—latitude 82.5°N—which lies 817 kilometres (508 mi) from the North Pole.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In latitude, Canada's most northerly point of land is Cape Columbia in Nunavut at 83°6′41″N, with its southern extreme at Middle Island in Lake Erie at 41°40′53″N.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In longitude, Canada's land extends from Cape Spear, Newfoundland, at 52°37′W, to Mount St.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada can be divided into seven physiographic regions: the Canadian Shield, the Interior Plains, the Great Lakes–St.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Lawrence Lowlands, the Appalachian region, the Western Cordillera, Hudson Bay Lowlands, and the Arctic Archipelago.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Boreal forests prevail throughout the country, ice is prominent in northern Arctic regions and through the Rocky Mountains, and the relatively flat Canadian Prairies in the southwest facilitate productive agriculture.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Lawrence River (in the southeast) where the lowlands host much of Canada's economic output.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada has over 2,000,000 lakes—563 of which are larger than 100 square kilometres (39 sq mi)—containing much of the world's fresh water.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] There are also fresh-water glaciers in the Canadian Rockies, the Coast Mountains, and the Arctic Cordillera.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada is geologically active, having many earthquakes and potentially active volcanoes.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Average winter and summer high temperatures across Canada vary from region to region.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Winters can be harsh in many parts of the country, particularly in the interior and Prairie provinces, which experience a continental climate, where daily average temperatures are near −15 °C (5 °F), but can drop below −40 °C (−40 °F) with severe wind chills.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In non-coastal regions, snow can cover the ground for almost six months of the year, while in parts of the north snow can persist year-round.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Coastal British Columbia has a temperate climate, with a mild and rainy winter.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] On the east and west coasts, average high temperatures are generally in the low 20s °C (70s °F), while between the coasts, the average summer high temperature ranges from 25 to 30 °C (77 to 86 °F), with temperatures in some interior locations occasionally exceeding 40 °C (104 °F).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Much of Northern Canada is covered by ice and permafrost.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The future of the permafrost is uncertain because the Arctic has been warming at three times the global average as a result of climate change in Canada.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada's annual average temperature over land has risen by 1.7 °C (3.1 °F), with changes ranging from 1.1 to 2.3 °C (2.0 to 4.1 °F) in various regions, since 1948.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The rate of warming has been higher across the North and in the Prairies.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In the southern regions of Canada, air pollution from both Canada and the United States—caused by metal smelting, burning coal to power utilities, and vehicle emissions—has resulted in acid rain, which has severely impacted waterways, forest growth, and agricultural productivity.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada is one of the largest greenhouse gas emitters globally, with emissions increased by 16.5 percent between 1990 and 2022.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada is divided into 15 terrestrial and five marine ecozones.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] These ecozones encompass over 80,000 classified species of Canadian wildlife, with an equal number yet to be formally recognized or discovered.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Although Canada has a low percentage of endemic species compared to other countries, due to human activities, invasive species, and environmental issues in the country, there are currently more than 800 species at risk of being lost.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] About 65 percent of Canada's resident species are considered "Secure".
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Over half of Canada's landscape is intact and relatively free of human development.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The boreal forest of Canada is considered to be the largest intact forest on Earth, with approximately 3,000,000 square kilometres (1,200,000 sq mi) undisturbed by roads, cities or industry.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Since the end of the last glacial period, Canada has consisted of eight distinct forest regions.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Approximately 12.1 percent of the nation's landmass and freshwater are conservation areas, including 11.4 percent designated as protected areas.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Approximately 13.8 percent of its territorial waters are conserved, including 8.9 percent designated as protected areas.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada's first National Park, Banff National Park was established in 1885.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada's oldest provincial park, Algonquin Provincial Park was established in 1893.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Established in 2015, Lake Superior National Marine Conservation Area is the world's largest freshwater protected area.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada's largest national wildlife region, established in 2018, is the Scott Islands Marine National Wildlife Area.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada is described as a "full democracy", with a tradition of liberalism, and an egalitarian, moderate political ideology.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Since the 1960s, an emphasis on social justice has been a distinguishing element of Canada's political culture.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Peace, order, and good government, alongside an Implied Bill of Rights, are founding principles of Canadian federalism.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] At the federal level, Canada has been dominated by two relatively centrist parties practising "brokerage politics": the centre-left leaning Liberal Party of Canada and the centre-right leaning Conservative Party of Canada (or its predecessors).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The historically predominant Liberals position themselves at the centre of the political scale.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Far-right and far-left politics have never been a prominent force in Canadian society.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada has a parliamentary system within the context of a constitutional monarchy—the monarchy of Canada being the foundation of the executive, legislative, and judicial branches.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The reigning monarch is also monarch of 14 other sovereign Commonwealth countries and Canada's 10 provinces.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The monarch appoints a representative, the governor general, on the advice of the prime minister, to carry out most of their ceremonial royal duties.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The monarchy is the source of sovereignty and authority in Canada.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] To ensure the stability of government, the governor general will usually appoint as prime minister the person who is the current leader of the political party that can obtain the confidence of a majority of members in the House.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The leader of the party with the second-most seats usually becomes the leader of the Official Opposition and is part of an adversarial parliamentary system intended to keep the government in check.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Parliament of Canada passes all federal statute laws.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] It comprises the monarch, the House of Commons, and the Senate.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] While Canada inherited the British concept of parliamentary supremacy, this was later, with the enactment of the Constitution Act, 1982, all but completely superseded by the American notion of the supremacy of the law.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Each of the 343 members of Parliament in the House of Commons is elected by simple plurality in an electoral district or riding.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The 105 members of the Senate, whose seats are apportioned on a regional basis, serve until age 75.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canadian federalism divides government responsibilities between the federal government and the 10 provinces.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Provincial legislatures are unicameral and operate in parliamentary fashion similar to the House of Commons.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada's three territories also have legislatures, but these are not sovereign, have fewer constitutional responsibilities than the provinces, and differ structurally from their provincial counterparts.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Constitution of Canada is the supreme law of the country and consists of written text and unwritten conventions.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The *Constitution Act, 1867* (known as the British North America Act, 1867 prior to 1982), affirmed governance based on parliamentary precedent and divided powers between the federal and provincial governments.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The *Statute of Westminster, 1931*, granted full autonomy, and the *Constitution Act, 1982*, ended all legislative ties to Britain, as well as adding a constitutional amending formula and the *Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms*.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The *Charter* guarantees basic rights and freedoms that usually cannot be overridden by any government; a notwithstanding clause allows Parliament and the provincial legislatures to override certain sections of the *Charter* for a period of five years.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada's judiciary interprets laws and has the power to strike down acts of Parliament that violate the constitution.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Supreme Court of Canada is the highest court, final arbiter, and has been led since 2017 by Richard Wagner, the Chief Justice of Canada.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The governor general appoints the court's nine members on the advice of the prime minister and minister of justice.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The federal Cabinet also appoints justices to superior courts in the provincial and territorial jurisdictions.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Common law prevails everywhere except Quebec, where civil law predominates.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Criminal law is solely a federal responsibility and is uniform throughout Canada.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Law enforcement, including criminal courts, is officially a provincial responsibility, conducted by provincial and municipal police forces.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In most rural and some urban areas, policing responsibilities are contracted to the federal Royal Canadian Mounted Police.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canadian Aboriginal law provides certain constitutionally recognized rights to land and traditional practices for Indigenous groups in Canada.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Various treaties and case laws were established to mediate relations between Europeans and many Indigenous peoples.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The role of Aboriginal law and the rights they support were reaffirmed by section 35 of the Constitution Act, 1982.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] These rights may include provision of services, such as healthcare through the Indian Health Transfer Policy, and exemption from taxation.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada is a federation composed of 10 federated states, called provinces, and three federal territories.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] These may be grouped into four main regions: Western Canada, Central Canada, Atlantic Canada, and Northern Canada (*Eastern Canada* refers to Central Canada and Atlantic Canada together).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Provinces and territories have responsibility for social programs such as healthcare, education, and social programs, as well as administration of justice (but not criminal law).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Although the provinces collect more revenue than the federal government, equalization payments are made by the federal government to ensure reasonably uniform standards of services and taxation are kept between the richer and poorer provinces.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada is recognized as a middle power for its role in global affairs with a tendency to pursue multilateral and international solutions.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Globalization has significantly influenced Canadian foreign policies, with the country known for its promotion of peace and security through mediation, and for providing aid to developing countries.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada and the United States have a long and complex relationship; historically close allies, they co-operate regularly on military campaigns and humanitarian efforts.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada also maintains historic and traditional ties to the United Kingdom and to France, along with both countries' former colonies through its membership in the Commonwealth of Nations and the *Organisation internationale de la Francophonie*.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada is noted for having a positive relationship with the Netherlands, owing, in part, to its contribution to the Dutch liberation during the Second World War.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada has diplomatic and consular offices in over 270 locations in approximately 180 foreign countries.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada promotes its domestically shared values through participating in multiple international organizations.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada was a founding member of the United Nations (UN) in 1945 and formed the North American Aerospace Defense Command together with the United States in 1958.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The country has membership in the World Trade Organization, the Five Eyes, the G7 and the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The country was a founding member of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum (APEC) in 1989 and joined the Organization of American States (OAS) in 1990.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada ratified the Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR) in 1948, and seven principal UN human rights conventions and covenants since then.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Alongside many domestic obligations, more than 3,000 Canadian Armed Forces (CAF) personnel are deployed in multiple foreign military operations.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Canadian unified forces comprise the Royal Canadian Navy, Canadian Army, and Royal Canadian Air Force.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The nation employs a professional, volunteer force of approximately 68,000 active personnel and 27,000 reserve personnel.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In March 2026, Canada achieved the NATO target of spending 2% of its GDP on defence for the 2026 fiscal year.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] This marks a significant increase from previous years—roughly 1.3% to 1.4% between 2021 and 2024.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada's role in developing *peacekeeping* and its participation in initiatives during the 20th century has played a major role in its positive global image.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Peacekeeping is deeply embedded in Canadian culture and a distinguishing feature that Canadians feel sets their foreign policy apart from the United States.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada has long been reluctant to participate in military interventions that are not sanctioned by the United Nations, such as the Vietnam War, the 2003 invasion of Iraq and 2026 Iran war.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Since the 21st century, Canadian direct participation in UN peacekeeping efforts has greatly declined.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The large decrease was a result of Canada directing its participation to UN-sanctioned military operations through the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, rather than directly through the UN.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The change to participation via NATO has resulted in a shift towards more militarized and deadly missions rather than traditional peacekeeping duties.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada's mixed-market economy is highly developed, ranking as the world's ninth-largest by nominal GDP as of 2023, at approximately US$2.221 trillion.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The country is one of the world's largest trading nations, with a highly globalized economy.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In 2021, Canadian trade in goods and services reached $2.016 trillion.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada's exports totalled over $637 billion, while its imported goods were worth over $631 billion, of which approximately $391 billion originated from the United States.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In 2018, Canada had a trade deficit in goods of $22 billion and a trade deficit in services of $25 billion.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Toronto Stock Exchange is the ninth-largest stock exchange in the world by market capitalization, listing over 1,500 companies with a combined market capitalization of over US$2 trillion.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Bank of Canada is the central bank of the country.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The minister of finance and minister of innovation, science, and industry use data from Statistics Canada to enable financial planning and develop economic policy.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada has a strong cooperative banking sector, with the world's highest per-capita membership in credit unions.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] It ranks low in the Corruption Perceptions Index (14th in 2023) and "is widely regarded as among the least corrupt countries of the world".
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] It ranks high in the Global Competitiveness Report (19th in 2024).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada's economy ranks above most Western nations on the Heritage Foundation's Index of Economic Freedom and experiences a relatively low level of income disparity.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The country's average household disposable income per capita is "well above" the OECD average.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada ranks among the lowest of the most developed countries for housing affordability and foreign direct investment.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The unemployment rate in 2025 was 6.8 percent.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Since the early 20th century, the growth of Canada's manufacturing, mining, and service sectors has transformed the nation from a largely rural economy to an urbanized, industrial one.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Canadian economy is dominated by the service industry, which employs about three-quarters of the country's workforce.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada has an unusually important primary sector, of which the forestry and petroleum industries are the most prominent components.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Many towns in northern Canada, where agriculture is difficult, are sustained by nearby mines or sources of timber.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada's economic integration with the United States has increased significantly since the Second World War.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Canada – United States Free Trade Agreement (FTA) of 1988 eliminated tariffs between the two countries, while the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) expanded the free-trade zone to include Mexico in 1994 (later replaced by the Canada–United States–Mexico Agreement).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] As of 2023, Canada is a signatory to 15 free trade agreements with 51 different countries.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada is one of the few developed nations that are net exporters of energy.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Atlantic Canada possess vast offshore deposits of natural gas, and Alberta hosts the fourth-largest oil reserves in the world.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The vast Athabasca oil sands and other oil reserves give Canada 13 percent of global oil reserves, constituting the world's third- or fourth-largest.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada is additionally one of the world's largest suppliers of agricultural products; the Canadian Prairies region is one of the most important global producers of wheat, canola, and other grains.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada's main exports are zinc, uranium, gold, nickel, platinoids, aluminum, steel, iron ore, coking coal, lead, copper, molybdenum, cobalt, and cadmium.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada has a sizeable manufacturing sector centred in southern Ontario and Quebec, with automobiles and aeronautics representing particularly important industries.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The country's fishing and tourism industries are also a key contributor to the economy.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] In 2020, Canada spent approximately $41.9 billion on domestic research and development, with supplementary estimates for 2022 at $43.2 billion.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] As of 2023, the country has produced 15 Nobel laureates in physics, chemistry, and medicine.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The country ranks seventh in the worldwide share of articles published in scientific journals, according to the Nature Index, and is home to the headquarters of a number of global technology firms.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada has one of the highest levels of Internet access in the world, with approximately 95 percent of its population aged 15 and above.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada's achievements in science and technology include the creation of the modern alkaline battery, the discovery of insulin, the development of the polio vaccine, and discoveries about the interior structure of the atomic nucleus.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Other major Canadian scientific contributions include the artificial cardiac pacemaker, mapping the visual cortex, the development of the electron microscope, plate tectonics, deep learning, multi-touch technology, and the identification of the first black hole, Cygnus X-1.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada has a long history of discovery in genetics, which include stem cells, site-directed mutagenesis, T-cell receptor, and the identification of the genes that cause Fanconi anemia, cystic fibrosis, and early-onset Alzheimer's disease, among numerous other diseases.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] The Canadian Space Agency runs an active space program focused on deep-space, planetary, and aviation research, along with rockets and satellites.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada launched its first satellite, Alouette 1, in 1962.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] It contributes to the International Space Station and is known for its robotic tools, such as multiple Canadarms.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p01] Canada has initiated many long-term projects, including the Radarsat satellite series and the Black Brant rocket series.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The 2021 Canadian census enumerated a total population of 36,991,981, an increase of around 5.2 percent over the 2016 figure.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] It is estimated that Canada's population surpassed 40,000,000 in 2023.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The main drivers of population growth are immigration and, to a lesser extent, natural growth.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canada has one of the highest per-capita immigration rates in the world, driven mainly by economic policy and family reunification.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] A record 483,390 immigrants were admitted in 2024.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canada leads the world in refugee resettlement; it resettled more than 47,600 in 2022.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] New immigrants settle mostly in major urban areas, such as Toronto, Montreal, and Vancouver.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canada's population density, at 4.2 inhabitants per square kilometre (11/sq mi), is among the lowest in the world, with approximately 95 percent of the population residing south of the 55th parallel north.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] About 80 percent of the population lives within 150 kilometres (93 mi) of the border with the contiguous United States.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canada is highly urbanized, with over 80 percent of the population living in urban centres.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The majority of Canadians (over 70 percent) live below the 49th parallel, with 50 percent of Canadians living south of 45°42′ (45.7 degrees) north.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The most densely populated part of the country is the Quebec City–Windsor Corridor in Southern Quebec and Southern Ontario along the Great Lakes and the St.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The majority of Canadians (81.1 percent) live in family households, 12.1 percent report living alone, and 6.8 percent live with other relatives or unrelated persons.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Fifty-one percent of households are couples with or without children, 8.7 percent are single-parent households, 2.9 percent are multigenerational households, and 29.3 percent are single-person households.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Respondents in the 2021 Canadian census self-reported over 450 "ethnic or cultural origins".
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Over 60 percent of Canadians reported a single origin, and 36 percent reported having multiple ethnic origins, thus the overall total is greater than 100 percent.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Of the 36.3 million people enumerated in 2021, approximately 25.4 million reported being "White", representing 69.8 percent of the population.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The Indigenous population representing 5 percent or 1.8 million people, grew by 9.4 percent compared to the non-Indigenous population, which grew by 5.3 percent from 2016 to 2021.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Between 2011 and 2016, the visible minority population rose by 18.4 percent.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] In 1961, about 300,000 people, less than two percent of Canada's population, were members of visible minority groups.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The 2021 census indicated that 8.3 million people, or almost one-quarter (23.0 percent) of the population, reported themselves as being or having been a landed immigrant or permanent resident in Canada—above the 1921 census previous record of 22.3 percent.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] In 2021, India, China, and the Philippines were the top three countries of origin for immigrants moving to Canada.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] A multitude of languages are used by Canadians, with English and French (the official languages) being the mother tongues of approximately 54 percent and 19 percent of Canadians, respectively.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canada's official bilingualism policies give citizens the right to receive federal government services in either English or French with official-language minorities guaranteed their own schools in all provinces and territories.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Quebec's 1974 *Official Language Act* established French as the only official language of the province.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Although more than 82 percent of French-speaking Canadians live in Quebec, there are substantial Francophone populations in New Brunswick, Alberta, and Manitoba, with Ontario having the largest French-speaking population outside Quebec.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] New Brunswick, the only officially bilingual province, has an Acadian French minority constituting 33 percent of the population.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] There are also clusters of Acadians in southwestern Nova Scotia, on Cape Breton Island, and in central and western Prince Edward Island.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Other provinces have no official languages as such, but French is used as a language of instruction, in courts, and for other government services, in addition to English.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Manitoba, Ontario, and Quebec allow for both English and French to be spoken in the provincial legislatures and laws are enacted in both languages.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] In Ontario, French has some legal status, but is not fully co-official.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] There are 11 Indigenous language groups, composed of more than 65 distinct languages and dialects.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Several Indigenous languages have official status in the Northwest Territories.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Inuktitut is the majority language in Nunavut and is one of three official languages in the territory.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] As of the 2021 census, just over 7.8 million Canadians listed a non-official language as their first language.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The country is also home to many sign languages, some of which are Indigenous.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] American Sign Language (ASL) is used across the country due to the prevalence of ASL in primary and secondary schools.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Quebec Sign Language (LSQ) is used primarily in Quebec.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canada is religiously diverse, encompassing a wide range of beliefs and customs.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The Constitution of Canada refers to God; however, Canada has no official church and the government is officially committed to religious pluralism.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Freedom of religion in Canada is a constitutionally protected right.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Rates of religious adherence have steadily decreased since the 1970s.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] With Christianity in decline after having once been central and integral to Canadian culture and daily life, Canada has become a post-Christian, secular state.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Although the majority of Canadians consider religion to be unimportant in their daily lives, they still believe in God.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The practice of religion is generally considered a private matter.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] According to the 2021 census, Christianity is the largest religion in Canada, with Roman Catholics representing 29.9 percent of the population having the most adherents.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Christians overall representing 53.3 percent of the population, are followed by people reporting irreligion or having no religion at 34.6 percent.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Other faiths include Islam (4.9 percent), Hinduism (2.3 percent), Sikhism (2.1 percent), Buddhism (1.0 percent), Judaism (0.9 percent), and Indigenous spirituality (0.2 percent).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canada has the second-largest national Sikh population, behind India.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Healthcare in Canada is delivered through the provincial and territorial systems of publicly funded health care, informally called Medicare.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] It is guided by the provisions of the *Canada Health Act* of 1984 and is universal.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Universal access to publicly funded health services "is often considered by Canadians as a fundamental value that ensures national healthcare insurance for everyone wherever they live in the country".
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Around 30 percent of Canadians' healthcare is paid for through the private sector.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] This mostly pays for services not covered or partially covered by Medicare, such as prescription drugs, dentistry and optometry.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Approximately 65 to 75 percent of Canadians have some form of supplementary health insurance; many receive it through their employers or access secondary social service programs.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] In common with many other developed countries, Canada is experiencing an increase in healthcare expenditures due to a demographic shift toward an older population, with more retirees and fewer people of working age.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] In 2021, the average age in Canada was 41.9 years.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] A 2016 report by the chief public health officer found that 88 percent of Canadians, one of the highest proportions of the population among G7 countries, indicated that they "had good or very good health".
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Eighty percent of Canadian adults self-report having at least one major risk factor for chronic disease: smoking, physical inactivity, unhealthy eating or excessive alcohol use.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canada has one of the highest rates of adult obesity among OECD countries, contributing to approximately 2.7 million cases of diabetes.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Four chronic diseases—cancer (leading cause of death), cardiovascular diseases, respiratory diseases, and diabetes—account for 65 percent of deaths in Canada.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] There are approximately 8 million people aged 15 and older with one or more disabilities in Canada.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] In 2024, the Canadian Institute for Health Information estimated that healthcare spending reached $372 billion, or 12.4 percent of Canada's GDP for that year.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] In 2022, Canada's per-capita spending on health expenditures ranked 12th among health-care systems in the OECD.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The Commonwealth Fund's 2021 report comparing the healthcare systems of the 11 most developed countries ranked Canada second-to-last.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Identified weaknesses were comparatively higher infant mortality rate, the prevalence of chronic conditions, long wait times, poor availability of after-hours care, and a lack of prescription drugs and dental coverage.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] An increasing problem in Canada's health system is a lack of healthcare professionals and hospital capacity.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Education in Canada is for the most part provided publicly, funded and overseen by federal, provincial, and local governments.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Education is within provincial jurisdiction and a province's curriculum is overseen by its government.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Education in Canada is generally divided into primary education, followed by secondary and post-secondary education.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Education in both English and French is available in most places across Canada.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canada has a large number of universities, almost all of which are publicly funded.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Established in 1663, Université Laval is the oldest post-secondary institution in Canada.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The nation's three top ranking universities are the University of Toronto, McGill, and the University of British Columbia.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The largest university is the University of Toronto, which has over 85,000 students.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] According to a 2022 report by the OECD, Canada is one of the most educated countries in the world; the country ranks first worldwide in the percentage of adults having tertiary education, with over 56 percent of Canadian adults having attained at least an undergraduate college or university degree.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canada spends an average of 5.3 percent of its GDP on education.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The country invests heavily in tertiary education (more than US$20,000 per student).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] As of 2022, 89 percent of adults aged 25 to 64 have earned the equivalent of a high-school degree, compared to an OECD average of 75 percent.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canada is influenced by British, French and Indigenous cultures and traditions.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] During the 20th century, Canadians with African, Caribbean, and Asian heritages have added to Canadian identity.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canada's culture draws influences from its broad range of constituent nationalities, and policies that promote a just society are constitutionally protected.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Since the 1960s, Canada has emphasized human rights and inclusiveness for all its people.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canadian identity shifted from primarily British-based to multicultural between the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The official state policy of multiculturalism is often cited as one of Canada's significant accomplishments and a key distinguishing element of Canadian identity.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] In Quebec, cultural identity is strong and there is a French Canadian culture that is distinct from English Canadian culture.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] As a whole, Canada is in theory a cultural mosaic of regional ethnic subcultures with diverse areas and ethnic enclaves.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canada's approach to governance emphasizing multiculturalism, which is based on selective immigration, social integration, and suppression of far-right politics, has wide public support.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canadians also identify with the country's foreign aid policies, peacekeeping roles, the national park system, and the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Themes of nature, pioneers, trappers, and traders played an important part in the early development of Canadian symbolism.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Modern symbols emphasize the country's geography, northern climate, lifestyles, and the Canadianization of traditional European and Indigenous symbols.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The use of the maple leaf as a symbol dates to the early 18th century in New France.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The maple leaf is depicted on Canada's current and previous flags and on the arms of Canada.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canada's official tartan, known as the "maple leaf tartan", reflects the colours of the maple leaf through the seasons—green in the spring, gold in the early autumn, red at the first frost, and brown after falling.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The arms of Canada are closely modelled after those of the United Kingdom, with French and distinctive Canadian elements replacing or added to those derived from the British version.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canadian cuisine items such as Canadian beer, maple syrup, Nanaimo bars, butter tarts, and the Quebec dishes of poutine and tourtière, alongside material items such as tuques, canoes and Hudson's Bay point blanket are considered as uniquely Canadian.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canadian coins feature many of these symbols: the loon on the $1 coin, the coat of arms on the 50¢ piece, and the beaver on the nickel.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] An image of the monarch appears on $20 bank notes and the obverse of coins.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canadian literature is often divided into French- and English-language literatures, which are rooted in the literary traditions of France and Britain, respectively.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The earliest Canadian narratives were of travel and exploration.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] This developed into three major themes of historical Canadian literature: nature, frontier life, and Canada's position within the world, all of which tie into the garrison mentality.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The evolution of Canadian literature is intricately linked to the country's historical and social contexts, often mirroring the challenges and changes in Canadian society.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] As Canadian literature progressed into the 20th and 21st centuries, it began to address a broader array of subjects and themes, such as women's rights, LGBTQ rights, immigrant experiences, environmental issues, the relationship with Indigenous peoples, and Canadian values and identity.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Financial support from governmental bodies, such as the Canada Council for the Arts and various provincial grant programs, facilitates the creation, publication, and promotion of works by Canadian authors.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Numerous Canadian authors have received international literary awards including the Nobel Prize in Literature, the Booker Prize, and the Pulitzer Prize for Fiction.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canadian literary awards and prizes include the Governor General's Literary Awards, the Giller Prize, the Latner Griffin Writers' Trust Poetry Prize, the Burt Award for First Nations, Inuit and Métis Literature and several accolades for literature aimed at children.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Art in Canada is marked by thousands of years of habitation by Indigenous peoples, and, in later times, artists have combined British, French, Indigenous, and American artistic traditions, at times embracing European styles while working to promote nationalism.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The nature of Canadian art reflects these diverse origins, as artists have taken their traditions and adapted these influences to reflect the reality of their lives in Canada.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The Group of Seven is often considered the first uniquely Canadian artistic group and style of painting.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Inuit art since the 1950s has been the traditional gift given to foreign dignitaries by the Canadian government.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Historically, the Catholic Church was the primary patron of art in early Canada, especially Quebec.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The Government of Canada has played a role in the development of art, through the department of Canadian Heritage by giving grants to art galleries, as well as by establishing and funding art schools and colleges across the country, and through the Canada Council for the Arts.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The Canada Council Art Bank also helps artists by buying and publicizing their work.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Great achievements in art in Canada are recognized through various awards and prizes, such as the Molson Prize, the Audain Prize for the Visual Arts, and the Governor General's Visual and Media Arts Awards.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canadian music reflects a variety of regional scenes.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canada has developed a vast music infrastructure that includes church halls, chamber halls, conservatories, academies, performing arts centres, record companies, radio stations, music charts, and television music video channels.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Government support programs, such as the Canada Music Fund, assist a wide range of musicians and entrepreneurs who create, produce and market original and diverse Canadian music.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] As a result of its cultural importance, as well as government initiatives and regulations, the Canadian music industry is one of the largest in the world, producing internationally renowned composers, musicians, and ensembles.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Achievements in music are recognized through various awards and prizes, most notably, the Juno Awards presented by the Canadian Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The country also hosts numerous music halls of fame with the Canadian Music Hall of Fame honouring musicians at the national level for their lifetime achievements.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] "God Save the King" has been used in Canada since the late 1700s and is the country's de facto royal anthem.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Patriotic music by Canadians dates back over 200 years, with "The Bold Canadian", written in 1812, popular throughout the 19th century.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] "The Maple Leaf Forever", written in 1866, was popular and served as an unofficial national anthem of English Canada.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] "O Canada", originally composed in French in 1880, also served as an unofficial national anthem during the 20th century and was adopted as the country's official anthem in 1980.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canada's media is highly autonomous, diverse, and very regionalized.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The *Broadcasting Act* declares "the system should serve to safeguard, enrich, and strengthen the cultural, political, social, and economic fabric of Canada".
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canada has a well-developed media sector, but its cultural output—particularly in English films, television shows, and magazines—is often overshadowed by imports from the United States.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] As a result, the preservation of a distinctly Canadian culture is supported by federal government programs, laws, and institutions such as the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (CBC), the National Film Board of Canada (NFB), and the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission (CRTC).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canadian mass media, both print and digital, and in both official languages, is largely dominated by a "handful of corporations".
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The largest of these corporations is the country's national public broadcaster, the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation, which also plays a significant role in producing domestic cultural content, operating its own radio and TV networks in both English and French.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] In addition to the CBC, some provincial governments offer their own public educational TV broadcast services as well, such as TVOntario and Télé-Québec.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Non-news media content in Canada, including film and television, is influenced both by local creators as well as by imports from the United States, the United Kingdom, Australia, and France.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] In an effort to reduce the amount of foreign-made media, government interventions in television broadcasting can include both regulation of content and public financing.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canadian tax laws limit foreign competition in magazine advertising.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canada's official national sports are ice hockey and lacrosse.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Other major professional games include curling, basketball, baseball, soccer, and football.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Great achievements in Canadian sports are recognized by numerous "Halls of Fame" and museums, such as Canada's Sports Hall of Fame.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canada shares several major professional sports leagues with the United States.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canadian teams in these leagues include seven franchises in the National Hockey League, three Major League Soccer teams, and one team in each of Major League Baseball and the National Basketball Association.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Other popular professional competitions include the Canadian Football League, National Lacrosse League, the Canadian Premier League, and the curling tournaments hosted by Curling Canada.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Canadians identified hockey as their preferred sport for viewing, followed by soccer and then basketball.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] In terms of participation, swimming was the most commonly reported sport by over one-third (35 percent) of Canadians in 2023.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] This was closely followed by cycling (33 percent) and running (27 percent).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] Sports such as golf, volleyball, badminton, bowling, and martial arts are also widely enjoyed at the youth and amateur levels.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/canada-p02] The country co-hosted the 2026 FIFA World Cup alongside Mexico and the United States.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] In these countries and around them are the areas that are the most linguistically diverse in the world (denoted in blue on the map).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] An **endangered language** or **moribund language** is a language that is at risk of disappearing as its speakers die out or shift to speaking other languages.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Language loss occurs when the language has no more native speakers and becomes a "dead" or "extinct language".
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] A dead language may still be studied through recordings or writings, but it is still considered dead or extinct once there are no more fluent speakers left.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Although languages have always become extinct throughout human history, factors currently accelerating the rate of language death include globalization, mass migration, linguistic imperialism, neocolonialism, and linguicide (language killing).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Language shift most commonly occurs when speakers switch to a language associated with social or economic power or one spoken more widely, leading to the gradual decline and eventual death of the endangered language.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] The process of language shift is often influenced by factors such as globalisation, economic authorities, and the perceived prestige of certain languages.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] The ultimate result is the loss of linguistic diversity and cultural heritage within affected communities.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] The general consensus is that between 6,000 and 7,000 languages are currently spoken.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Some linguists estimate that between 50% and 90% of them will be severely endangered or dead by the year 2100.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] The 20 most common languages, each with more than 50 million speakers, are spoken by 50% of the world's population, but most languages are spoken by fewer than 10,000 people.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] The first step towards language death is *potential endangerment*.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] This is when a language faces strong external pressure, but there are still communities of speakers who pass the language to their children.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Once a language has reached the endangerment stage, there are only a few speakers left and children are, for the most part, not learning the language.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] The third stage of language extinction is *seriously endangered*.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] During this stage, a language is unlikely to survive another generation and will soon be extinct.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] The fourth stage is *moribund*, followed by the fifth stage *extinction*.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Many projects are under way aimed at preventing or slowing language loss by revitalizing endangered languages and promoting education and literacy in minority languages, often involving joint projects between language communities and linguists.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Across the world, many countries have enacted specific legislation aimed at protecting and stabilizing the language of indigenous speech communities.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Recognizing that most of the world's endangered languages are unlikely to be revitalized, many linguists are also working on documenting the thousands of languages of the world about which little or nothing is known.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Some widely spoken languages have endangered regional dialects, such as the varieties of English spoken on the American east coast, such as Eastern New England English.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] The total number of contemporary languages in the world is not known, and it is not well defined what constitutes a separate language as opposed to a dialect.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Estimates vary depending on the extent and means of the research undertaken, and the definition of a distinct language and the current state of knowledge of remote and isolated language communities.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] The number of known languages varies over time as some of them become extinct and others are newly discovered.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] An accurate number of languages in the world was not yet known until the use of universal, systematic surveys in the later half of the twentieth century.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] The majority of linguists in the early twentieth century refrained from making estimates.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Before then, estimates were frequently the product of guesswork and very low.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] One of the most active research agencies is SIL International, which maintains a database, Ethnologue, kept up to date by the contributions of linguists globally.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Ethnologue's 2005 count of languages in its database, excluding duplicates in different countries, was 6,912, of which 32.8% (2,269) were in Asia, and 30.3% (2,092) in Africa.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] This contemporary tally must be regarded as a variable number within a range.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Areas with a particularly large number of languages that are nearing extinction include: Eastern Siberia, Central Siberia, Northern Australia, Central America, and the Northwest Pacific Plateau.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Other hotspots are Oklahoma and the Southern Cone of South America.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Almost all of the study of language endangerment has been with spoken languages.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] A UNESCO study of endangered languages does not mention sign languages.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] However, some sign languages are also endangered, such as Alipur Village Sign Language (AVSL) of India, Adamorobe Sign Language of Ghana, Ban Khor Sign Language of Thailand, and Plains Indian Sign Language.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Many sign languages are used by small communities; small changes in their environment (such as contact with a larger sign language or dispersal of the deaf community) can lead to the endangerment and loss of their traditional sign language.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Methods are being developed to assess the vitality of sign languages.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Many languages, for example some in Indonesia, have tens of thousands of speakers, but are endangered because children are no longer learning them, and speakers are shifting to using the national language (e.g.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Indonesian) in place of local languages.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] In contrast, a language with only 500 speakers might be considered very much alive if it is the primary language of a community, and is the first (or only) spoken language of all children in that community.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] UNESCO's *Atlas of the World's Languages in Danger* categorises 2,473 languages by level of endangerment.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] As of November 2025, these categories are currently being reviewed by UNESCO to ensure they reflect the most up-to-date information on language vitality worldwide.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Using an alternative scheme of classification, linguist Michael E.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Krauss defines languages as "safe" if it is considered that children will probably be speaking them in 100 years; "endangered" if children will probably not be speaking them in 100 years (approximately 60–80% of languages fall into this category) and "moribund" if children are not speaking them now.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Many scholars have devised techniques for determining whether languages are endangered.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] One of the earliest is GIDS (Graded Intergenerational Disruption Scale) proposed by Joshua Fishman in 1991.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] In 2011 an entire issue of *Journal of Multilingual and Multicultural Development* was devoted to the study of ethnolinguistic vitality, Vol.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] 32.2, 2011, with several authors presenting their own tools for measuring language vitality.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] A number of other published works on measuring language vitality have been published, prepared by authors with varying situations and applications in mind.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Any natural disaster severe enough to wipe out an entire population of native language speakers has the capability of endangering a language.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] An example of this is the languages spoken by the people of the Andaman Islands, who were seriously affected by the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] This has often happened when nation-states, as they work to promote a single national culture, limit the opportunities for using minority languages in the public sphere, schools, the media, and elsewhere, sometimes even prohibiting them altogether.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Sometimes ethnic groups are forcibly resettled, or children may be removed to be schooled away from home, or otherwise have their chances of cultural and linguistic continuity disrupted.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] This has happened in the case of many Native American, Louisiana French and Australian languages, as well as European and Asian minority languages such as Breton, Occitan, or Alsatian in France and Kurdish in Turkey.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] The movement of people into urban areas can force people to learn the language of their new environment.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Eventually, later generations will lose the ability to speak their native language, leading to endangerment.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Once urbanization takes place, new families who live there will be under pressure to speak the lingua franca of the city.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Intermarriage can also cause language endangerment, as there will always be pressure to speak one language to each other.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] This may lead to children only speaking the more common language spoken between the married couple.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Often multiple of these causes act at the same time.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Poverty, disease and disasters often affect minority groups disproportionately, for example causing the dispersal of speaker populations and decreased survival rates for those who stay behind.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Among the causes of language endangerment cultural, political and economic marginalization accounts for most of the world's language endangerment.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Scholars distinguish between several types of marginalization: Economic dominance negatively affects minority languages when poverty leads people to migrate towards the cities or to other countries, thus dispersing the speakers.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Cultural dominance occurs when literature and higher education is only accessible in the majority language.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Political dominance occurs when education and political activity is carried out exclusively in a majority language.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Historically, in colonies, and elsewhere where speakers of different languages have come into contact, some languages have been considered superior to others: often one language has attained a dominant position in a country.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Speakers of endangered languages may themselves come to associate their language with negative values such as poverty, illiteracy and social stigma, causing them to wish to adopt the dominant language that is associated with social and economical progress and modernity.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Immigrants moving into an area may lead to the endangerment of the autochthonous language.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Dialects and accents have seen similar levels of endangerment during the 21st century due to similar reasons.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Language endangerment affects both the languages themselves and the people that speak them.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] This also affects the essence of a culture.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] As communities lose their language, they often lose parts of their cultural traditions that are tied to that language.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Examples include songs, myths, poetry, local remedies, ecological and geological knowledge, as well as language behaviors that are not easily translated.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Furthermore, the social structure of one's community is often reflected through speech and language behavior.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] This pattern is even more prominent in dialects.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] This may in turn affect the sense of identity of the individual and the community as a whole, producing a weakened social cohesion as their values and traditions are replaced with new ones.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] This is sometimes characterized as anomie.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Losing a language may also have political consequences as some countries confer different political statuses or privileges on minority ethnic groups, often defining ethnicity in terms of language.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] In turn, communities that lose their language may also lose political legitimacy as a community with special collective rights.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Language can also be considered as scientific knowledge in topics such as medicine, philosophy, botany, and more.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] It reflects a community's practices when dealing with the environment and each other.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] When a language is lost, this knowledge is often lost as well.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] In contrast, language revitalization is correlated with better health outcomes in indigenous communities.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] During language loss—sometimes referred to as *obsolescence* in the linguistic literature—the language that is being lost generally undergoes changes as speakers make their language more similar to the language that they are shifting to.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] For example, gradually losing grammatical or phonological complexities that are not found in the dominant language.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Generally the accelerated pace of language endangerment is considered to be a problem by linguists and by the speakers.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] However, some linguists, such as the phonetician Peter Ladefoged, have argued that language death is a natural part of the process of human cultural development, and that languages die because communities stop speaking them for their own reasons.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Ladefoged argued that linguists should simply document and describe languages scientifically, but not seek to interfere with the processes of language loss.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] A similar view has been argued at length by linguist Salikoko Mufwene, who sees the cycles of language death and emergence of new languages through creolization as a continuous ongoing process.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] A majority of linguists do consider that language loss is an ethical problem, as they consider that most communities would prefer to maintain their languages if given a real choice.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] They also consider it a scientific problem, because language loss on the scale currently taking place will mean that future linguists will only have access to a fraction of the world's linguistic diversity, therefore their picture of what human language is—and can be—will be limited.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Some linguists consider linguistic diversity to be analogous to biological diversity, and compare language endangerment to wildlife endangerment.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Linguists, members of endangered language communities, governments, nongovernmental organizations, and international organizations such as UNESCO and the European Union are actively working to save and stabilize endangered languages.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Once a language is determined to be endangered, there are three steps that can be taken in order to stabilize or rescue the language.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] The first is language documentation, the second is language revitalization and the third is language maintenance.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Language documentation is the documentation in writing and audio-visual recording of grammar, vocabulary, and oral traditions (e.g. stories, songs, religious texts) of endangered languages.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] It entails producing descriptive grammars, collections of texts and dictionaries of the languages, and it requires the establishment of a secure archive where the material can be stored once it is produced so that it can be accessed by future generations of speakers or scientists.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Language revitalization, also known as *language revival* or *reversing language shift,* is the process by which a language community attempts to increase the number of active speakers of the endangered language, typically through political, community, and educational means.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] For case studies of this process, see Anderson (2014).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Applied linguistics and education are helpful in revitalizing endangered languages.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Vocabulary and courses are available online for a number of endangered languages.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Language maintenance refers to the support given to languages that need for their survival to be protected from outsiders who can ultimately affect the number of speakers of a language.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] UNESCO seeks to prevent language extinction by promoting and supporting the language in education, culture, communication and information, and science.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] Another option is "post-vernacular maintenance": the teaching of some words and concepts of the lost language, rather than revival proper.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/critically-endangered-language] As of June 2012 the United States has a J-1 specialist visa, which allows indigenous language experts who do not have academic training to enter the U.S. as experts aiming to share their knowledge and expand their skills.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] An **extinct language** or **dead language** is a language with no living native speakers.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] A **heritage language**, or sometimes a **dormant language**, is an extinct language that still serves as a symbol of ethnic identity to an ethnic group; these languages are often undergoing a process of revitalisation.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] Languages that have first-language speakers are known as living languages.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] Languages have typically become extinct as a result of the process of cultural assimilation leading to language shift, and the gradual abandonment of a native language in favor of a foreign *lingua franca*.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] As of the 2000s, a total of roughly 7,000 natively spoken languages existed worldwide.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] Most of these are minor languages in danger of extinction; one estimate published in 2004 expected that some 90% of the languages spoken at that time will have become extinct by 2050.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] Normally the transition from a spoken to an extinct language occurs when a language undergoes language death by being directly replaced by a different one.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] For example, many Native American languages were replaced by Dutch, English, French, Portuguese, or Spanish as a result of European colonization of the Americas.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] After a language has ceased to be spoken as a first language, it may continue to exist as learned, second language, such as Latin.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] This is accomplished by periodizing English and German as Old; for Latin, an apt clarifying adjective is Classical, which also normally includes designation of high or formal register.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] Minor languages are endangered mostly due to economic and cultural globalization, cultural assimilation, and development.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] With increasing economic integration on national and regional scales, people find it easier to communicate and conduct business in the dominant lingua francas of world commerce: English, Mandarin Chinese, Spanish, and French.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] Second, the more gradual process of language death may occur over several generations.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] The third and most rare outcome is for the pressured group to maintain as much of its native language as possible, while borrowing elements of the dominant language's grammar (replacing all, or portions of, the grammar of the original language).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] A now disappeared language may leave a substantial trace as a substrate in the language that replaces it.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] There have, however, also been cases where the language of higher prestige did not displace the native language but left a superstrate influence.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] The French language for example shows evidence both of a Celtic substrate and a Frankish superstrate.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] Institutions such as the education system, as well as (often global) forms of media such as the Internet, television, and print media play a significant role in the process of language loss.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] For example, when people migrate to a new country, their children attend school in the country, and the schools are likely to teach them in the majority language of the country rather than their parents' native language.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] Language death can also be the explicit goal of government policy.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] For example, part of the "kill the Indian, save the man" policy of American Indian boarding schools and other measures was to prevent Native Americans from transmitting their native language to the next generation and to punish children who spoke the language of their culture of origin.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] The French vergonha policy likewise had the aim of eradicating minority languages.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] Language revival is the attempt to re-introduce an extinct language in everyday use by a new generation of native speakers.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] The optimistic neologism "sleeping beauty languages" has been used to express such a hope, though scholars usually refer to such languages as dormant.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] In practice, this has only happened on a large scale successfully once: the revival of the Hebrew language.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] Hebrew had survived for millennia since the Babylonian exile as a liturgical language, but not as a vernacular language.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] Revival attempts for minor extinct languages with no status as a liturgical language typically have more modest results.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] The Cornish language revival has proven at least partially successful: after a century of effort there are 3,500 claimed native speakers, enough for UNESCO to change its classification from "extinct" to "critically endangered".
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] A Livonian language revival movement to promote the use of the Livonian language has managed to train a few hundred people to have some knowledge of it.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] This is a list of languages reported as having become extinct since 2010.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/extinct-language] For a more complete list, see Lists of extinct languages.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/international-congress-of-linguists] The **International Congress of Linguists** (**ICL**) takes place every five years, under the governance of the Permanent International Committee of Linguists (PICL) / *Comité International Permanent des Linguistes* (CIPL).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/international-congress-of-linguists] The 19th ICL was held in Geneva, Switzerland in 2013.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/international-congress-of-linguists] The 20th ICL was held in Cape Town, South Africa from 2–6 July 2018 on the topic of "The Diversity of Language".
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/international-congress-of-linguists] The next (21st) ICL was originally planned to take place in Kazan (Tatarstan), Russia) from 25 June to 2 July 2023.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/international-congress-of-linguists] However, due to the Russian invasion of Ukraine, the venue was changed and the Congress moved by one year.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/international-congress-of-linguists] It took place in Poznań, Poland at the Adam Mickiewicz University, 8–14 September 2024.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/international-congress-of-linguists] The next, 22nd Congress will be held on 23–29 July 2028 in Leiden, Netherlands as a centenary of CIPL.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/international-congress-of-linguists] The proposed title is World of Languages.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/international-congress-of-linguists] The ICL was started in April 1928 in The Hague, where it organized its first edition, and subsequent editions have been held in cities such as Geneva in 1931, Rome in 1933 and Copenhagen in 1936.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/international-congress-of-linguists] The first congress has been read as marking an intellectual split of the emergent discipline of linguistics from traditional philology, though in 1952, the seventh congress was held in London, hosted by the Philological Society.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/international-congress-of-linguists] A more recent congress took place in Paris in 1997.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/international-congress-of-linguists] The 18th International Congress of Linguists took place in 2008 in the city of Seoul, South Korea.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/international-congress-of-linguists] The Swiss Linguistics Society (SSG) proposed that the 19th congress would be organized in Ferdinand de Saussure’s city Geneva, one century after he died, to commemorate his important contributions to the field of linguistics.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/international-congress-of-linguists] The events took place from July 21 to July 27, 2013.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/international-congress-of-linguists] The 19th ICL was about the *language-cognition interface*, a topic of cognitive linguistics based on the foundational work of Ferdinand de Saussure, a Swiss linguist who is widely considered one of the fathers of 20th-century linguistics.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/international-congress-of-linguists] During the Congress, several sessions were held about major aspects of linguistics, including the origin of language, phonology, morphology, syntax, semantics, pragmatics, psycholinguistics, and sociolinguistics.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) **Red List of Threatened Species**, also known as the **IUCN Red List** or **Red Data Book**, founded in 1964, is an inventory of the global conservation status and extinction risk of biological species.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] A series of Regional Red Lists, which assess the risk of extinction to species within a political management unit, are also produced by countries and organizations.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] Major species assessors include BirdLife International, the Institute of Zoology (the research division of the Zoological Society of London), the World Conservation Monitoring Centre, and many Specialist Groups within the IUCN Species Survival Commission (SSC).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] Collectively, assessments by these organizations and groups account for nearly half the species on the Red List.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] The IUCN aims to have the category of every species re-evaluated at least every ten years, and every five years if possible.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] This is done in a peer reviewed manner through IUCN Species Survival Commission Specialist Groups (SSC), which are Red List Authorities (RLA) responsible for a species, group of species or specific geographic area, or in the case of BirdLife International, an entire class (Aves).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] The red list unit works with staff from the IUCN Global Species Programme as well as current program partners to recommend new partners or networks to join as new Red List Authorities.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] The number of species which have been assessed for the Red List has been increasing over time.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] As of 2023, of 150,388 species surveyed, 42,108 are considered at risk of extinction because of human activity, in particular overfishing, hunting, and land development.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] Initially the Red Data Lists were designed for specialists and were issued in a loose-leaf format that could be easily changed.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] The first two volumes of Red Lists were published in 1966 by conservationist Noel Simon, one for mammals and one for birds.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] The third volume that appeared covered reptiles and amphibians.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] In 1970, the IUCN published volume 5 in this series.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] This was the first Red Data List which focused on plants (angiosperms only), compiled by Ronald Melville.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] The final volume created in the loose leaf style was volume 4 on freshwater fishes.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] This was published in 1979 by Robert Rush Miller.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] The first attempt to create a Red Data Book for a nonspecialist public came in 1969 with *The Red Book: Wildlife in Danger*.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] This book covered various groups but was predominantly about mammals and birds, with smaller sections on reptiles, amphibians, fishes, and plants.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] The 2006 Red List, released on 4 May 2006 evaluated 40,168 species as a whole, plus an additional 2,160 subspecies, varieties, aquatic stocks, and subpopulations.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] On 12 September 2007, the World Conservation Union (IUCN) released the **2007 IUCN Red List of Threatened Species**.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] Russ Mittermeier, chief of Swiss-based IUCN's Primate Specialist Group, stated that 16,306 species are endangered with extinction, 188 more than in 2006 (total of 41,415 species on the Red List).
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] The Red List includes the Sumatran orangutan (*Pongo abelii*) in the Critically Endangered category and the Bornean orangutan (*Pongo pygmaeus*) in the Endangered category.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] The 2008 Blue List was released on 6 October 2008 at the IUCN World Conservation Congress in Barcelona and "confirmed an extinction crisis, with almost one in four [mammals] at risk of disappearing forever".
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] The study shows at least 1,141 of the 5,487 mammals on Earth are known to be threatened with extinction, and 836 are listed as Data Deficient.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] The Red List of 2012 was released 19 July 2012 at Rio+20 Earth Summit; nearly 2,000 species were added, with 4 species to the extinct list, 2 to the rediscovered list.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] The IUCN assessed a total of 63,837 species which revealed 19,817 are threatened with extinction.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] 3,947 were described as "critically endangered" and 5,766 as "endangered", while more than 10,000 species are listed as "vulnerable".
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] At threat are 41% of amphibian species, 33% of reef-building corals, 30% of conifers, 25% of mammals, and 13% of birds.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] The IUCN Red List has listed 132 species of plants and animals from India as "Critically Endangered".
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] Species are classified by the IUCN Red List into nine groups, specified through criteria such as rate of decline, population size, area of geographic distribution, and degree of population and distribution fragmentation.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] There is an emphasis on the acceptability of applying any criteria in the absence of high quality data including suspicion and potential future threats, "so long as these can reasonably be supported".
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] In the IUCN Red List, "threatened" embraces the categories of Critically Endangered, Endangered, and Vulnerable.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] In the 2001 framework, *Near Threatened* and *Least Concern* became their own categories, while *Conservation Dependent* was removed and its contents merged into *Near Threatened*.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] The tag of "possibly extinct" (PE) is used by Birdlife International, the Red List Authority for birds for the IUCN Red List.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] BirdLife International has recommended PE become an official tag for Critically Endangered species, and this has now been adopted, along with a "Possibly Extinct in the Wild" tag for species with populations surviving in captivity but likely to be extinct in the wild.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] All new IUCN assessments since 2001 have used version 3.1 of the categories and criteria.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] In 1997, the IUCN Red List received criticism on the grounds of secrecy (or at least poor documentation) surrounding the sources of its data.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] These allegations have led to efforts by the IUCN to improve its documentation and data quality, and to include peer reviews of taxa on the Red List.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] The list is also open to petitions against its classifications, on the basis of documentation or criteria.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] In the November 2016 issue of *Science Advances*, a research article claims there are serious inconsistencies in the way species are classified by the IUCN.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] The researchers contend that the IUCN's process of categorization is "out-dated, and leaves room for improvement", and further emphasize the importance of readily available and easy-to-include geospatial data, such as satellite and aerial imaging.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] Their conclusion questioned not only the IUCN's method but also the validity of where certain species fall on the List.
[src:atlas-of-the-world-s-languages-in-danger/iucn-red-list] They believe that combining geographical data can significantly increase the number of species that need to be reclassified to a higher risk category.
